03911nam a22005655i 9780822393818DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20112011ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223938187 a10.1515/97808223938182doi  a(DE-B1597)553924  a(OCoLC)753627607  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aJC571b.H474 2011 7aSOC0280002bisacsh04a3232221 aHesford, Wendy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSpectacular Rhetorics :bHuman Rights Visions, Recognitions, Feminisms /cWendy Hesford. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b14 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNext Wave: New Directions in Women's Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOne Human Rights Visions and Recognitions -- tTwo Staging Terror Spectacles -- tThree Witnessing Rape Warfare: Suspending the Spectacle -- tFour Global Sex Work, Victim Identities, and Cybersexualities -- tFive Spectacular Childhoods: Sentimentality and the Politics of (In)visibility -- tConclusion: Posthumanism, Human Rights, and the Humanities -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSpectacular Rhetorics is a rigorous analysis of the rhetorical frameworks and narratives that underlie human rights law, shape the process of cultural and legal recognition, and delimit public responses to violence and injustice. Integrating visual and textual criticism, Wendy S. Hesford scrutinizes "spectacular rhetoric," the use of visual images and rhetoric to construct certain bodies, populations, and nations as victims and incorporate them into human rights discourses geared toward Westerners, chiefly Americans. Hesford presents a series of case studies critiquing the visual representations of human suffering in documentary films, photography, and theater. In each study, she analyzes works addressing a prominent contemporary human rights cause, such as torture and unlawful detention, ethnic genocide and rape as a means of warfare, migration and the trafficking of women and children, the global sex trade, and child labor. Through these studies, she demonstrates how spectacular rhetoric activates certain cultural and national narratives and social and political relations, consolidates identities through the politics of recognition, and configures material relations of power and difference to produce and, ultimately, to govern human rights subjects.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aHuman rights advocacy. 0aHuman rights. 0aWomen's rights. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822393818zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822393818423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822393818.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles